This thread may have already gone stale, but just in case not...<p>I&#x27;ve found that treating configuration settings as &quot;first class abstractions&quot; in the Domain Model pays off quite nicely.  By this, I mean grouping related settings into an immutable class which is given the configuration settings provider in one of its constructors.  If there are reasonable defaults for <i>all</i> settings, then having a no-args constructor may be acceptable as well.<p>For example, in Scala I have types such as:<p><pre>
// Assume &#x27;config&#x27; is what can read external configuration
case class NetworkSettings (config : SomeConfigReader)
{
   val rootPath = &quot;company-name.project.network&quot;;<p><pre><code>   host : String = config.stringEntryOrDefault (s&quot;${rootPath}.host&quot;, &quot;localhost&quot;);
   port : Int = config.intEntryOrDefault (s&quot;{rootPath}.port&quot;, 1234);

   // etc.</code></pre>
}
</pre><p>Of course, this pattern could be used before or instead of having the ability to externalize configuration parameters.
